properties.title: Mayborn
images: In 1914, Mayborn was the first building built on the new Hillsboro campus.
This is a photo of Mayborn.
It was originally tasked for the instruction of Industrial Arts.
It was renamed in 1978 after Peabody trustee Frank W. Mayborn.

properties.title: Barnard Observatory
images: Barnard observatory was named for Edward E. Barnard who used the six inch refractor telescope to discover comets.
The observatory was razed in 1952 due to the telescope's lack of utility given the industrial haze and light pollution in Nashville.
The observatory was designed by Chancellor Landon C. Garland who also served as a Professor of Physics and Astronomy.

properties.title: Kirkland Hall
images: The cornerstone for Old Main, now Kirkland Hall, was laid on April 28, 1874.
Classes would begin in this building in a year the following fall with a little over 200 students.
Old Main was the primary hub of the university in the early years.
Old Main has been known as Main Building, University Hall, College Hall, and, finally, Kirkland Hall.
On April 20, 1905 disaster would strike the University as a fire would destroy much of the building.
The fire would consume all but 4,000 volumes of the nearly 40,000 volumes in the library.
The building was remade in the image of the town hall of Siena, with the addition of the battlements on the roof and the singular bell tower.
Kirkland Hall has become the architectural symbol of the University.
Kirkland Hall was designed by a local Nashville architect, William C. Smith. The iconic building now serves as the administrative building.

properties.title: Barnard Hall and Vanderbilt Hall
images: These twin dormitories were completed in 1957 and were the last of the Collegiate Gothic style to be added to campus.
Barnard Hall is named for Edward E. Barnard, a 19th century  astronomer, known as a ranking authority on the Milky Way.
Vanderbilt Hall is named for Frederick Vanderbilt, the Commodore's grandson, who left a large portion of his estate to the University.
Vanderbilt/Barnard Halls still serve as an upperclassmen dormitory.

properties.title: Benson Science Hall
images: Old Science was built in 1880 in the Victorian style common to campus at the time.
Old Science is unique in that it is not aligned with either of the campus' main axes but lies where they intersect.
Now known as Benson Science Hall, the building was dedicated to Robert Green Benson who established a one million dollar trust fund to restore the building.

properties.title: North Hall
images: North Hall was built in 1929 as a graduate dormitory.
North Hall was built in the Classical Revival style as evidenced by the entablatures and balustraded roof.
Now known as North House, it houses approximately 176 first-year students.
The building underwent an extensive renovation in 1989 and features an atrium on the sixth floor.

properties.title: Statue of Harold Stirling Vanderbilt
images: Harold Stirling Vanderbilt served as the President of the Board of Trustees during a period of unprecedented growth (1955-1968).
This statue was placed on the edge of library lawn to commemorate his service and contribution to the university.

properties.title: Benton Chapel
images: Benton Chapel was completed as part of the Divinity School Quadrangle in 1959.
The bronze door handles on the front of the chapel are of the Archangels, Michael and Gabriel, complete with their respective horn and sword.
The rear exterior wall features three crosses formed by bricks extending from the wall.
The interior features several stained glass windows, with most notably, the 'Word of God' window that features the the name of God written in Greek.
Services are still head every week at Benton Chapel and the space serves as a hub of campus religious life.

properties.title: Student Cottages on West Side Row
images: These buildings were the earliest student housing built on campus.
There were initially six identical cottages constructed in 1886 and 1887.
Students named the cottages Alpha, Belleview, Cumberland, Delphi, Euclid, and Franklin in that order starting at West End.
The buildings currently house the Women's Center, a LGBQTI Center, and various Greek student organizations.

properties.title: Buttrick Hall
images: Buttrick Hall was built in 1928 to house the biology department and had a greenhouse attached to it.
The construction was accompanied by that of Garland and Calhoun Halls as an effort to bolster the liberal arts at the University.
Buttrick Hall is currently the home to state of the art classroom space, faculty and administrative offices

properties.title: Neely Auditorium
images: Neely Auditorium was built in 1925 as a campus chapel and central meeting hall.
The building had 1,100 pews that could accommodate every undergraduate as well as their professors.
Vanderbilt would use the auditorium for graduation exercises from 1925 to 1948.
It is currently home to the Theatre department and the department's student production organization.
You can view one of the original pews in Neely's lobby.

properties.title: Vaughn Home
images: Vaughn Home was one of the seven original faculty houses built on campus. It was Residence Five.
The building has served as a residence for married faculty, a dormitory for men and for women.
It has also been offices for the departments of romance languages and teaching assistants in western civilization.
It presently houses the Robert Penn Warren Center for the Humanities.
Vaughn Home is named after William J Vaughn, a mathematics professor that lived here in the early years of the University.

properties.title: Garland Hall
images: Garland Hall was built in 1928 along with Buttrick and Calhoun Halls to bolster liberal arts at the University.
Garland Hall is currently home to Anthropology, Sociology and Religious Studies Departments.
Bust of Landon Cabell Garland, First Vanderbilt Chancellor 1875 - 1893

properties.title: Tolman Hall and Old Kissam Cornerstone
images: Tolman Hall was constructed in 1947, following World War II, to accommodate all of the returning soldiers that were enrolling in college in very large numbers.
In the immediate years after World War II, veterans would comprise over half of all students enrolled at Vanderbilt.
The inscribed cornerstone from Old Kissam Hall is embedded as a plaque into the front left fa�ade of Tolman Hall. Tolman Hall still serves as an upperclassmen dormitory.

properties.title: Central Library and Library Lawn
images: Library Lawn was originally the site of Old Wesley Hall.
Construction of the Library began in 1940 and included amenities such as air conditioning and an Air Raid Shelter.
The architect's plans originally called for the building to be 12 stories high.
The H. Fort Flowers Graduate Wing was built in 1969.
The Central Library is one of eight libraries across the campus.
The empty space left available by the removal of the ruins of Old Wesley Hall was dedicated on became the Library Lawn.
The idea of Joint University Libraries was the brainchild of Chancellor Carmichael.
The organization of the new system was led by A. Frederick Kuhlman, the Director of Libraries from 1936-1960.

properties.title: Alumni Memorial Hall
images: Alumni Memorial Hall was built in 1925 as the student center in the Collegiate Gothic style.
Alumni Memorial Hall was built in the Collegiate Gothic style to mirror the Medical School and Neely Auditorium.
In the Memorial Room the names of the forty-four Vanderbilt students that lost their lives during World War I are carved into the mantels.
AMH recently underwent significant renovations and currently houses the Writing Studio and the Learning Center.

properties.title: Calhoun Hall
images: Calhoun Hall was built in 1928 to house the departments of social sciences and humanities.
The construction of Calhoun Hall was accompanied by that of Garland and Buttirck Halls as an effort to bolster the liberal arts at the University.
The campus bookstore was housed in Calhoun Hall from 1928 to 1948.
It also housed the Divinity Library after Old Wesley Hall burned down and currently houses Economics, Communications, and Political Science.

properties.title: East Hall
images: East Hall was built in 1924 as a women's dormitory.
Now known as  East House, it provides accommodations for approximately 100 students.
East Hall was built in the Classical Revival style as evidenced by the entablatures and balustraded roof.
The building was completely renovated from 1987 to 1988.

properties.title: The Bur Oak
images: The Bur Oak (Quercus macrocarpa) is possibly the oldest living thing on the Vanderbilt Campus.
It is perhaps a little over 300 years old.
The average lifespan of a Bur Oak is between 200 to 400 years as is common with most species of oak.

properties.title: Old Gym
images: The Old Gym was designed by Peter J. Williamson in 1880 and built in the Victorian Gothic style.
It is now listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
It served as the social and recreational hub of the University.

The building would see the addition of a basketball gymnasium in 1920, only later to be removed in 1964. The building was built with funds provided by William Henry Vanderbilt, the son of Commodore Vanderbilt.

properties.title: Ginkgo Biloba
images: The Gingko tree has no living relatives and can be found in the fossil record as far back as 270 million years ago.
The tree is native to China and is used in traditional Chinese medicine as a memory and concentration enhancer.
The tree is deep rooted and resistant to wind and snow damage which enables it to thrive in the variable Nashville weather.
Ginkgos are dioecious, with separate sexes, some trees being female and others being male.
The easiest way to tell the difference between the trees is the pungent odor that emanates from the seeds female trees drop during the spring.

properties.title: Wesley Hall
images: Wesley Hall burned February 19, 1932, on the site that is now Library Lawn.  The disaster occurred at the height of the Great Depression.
Wesley Hall was the home of the Biblical School and was a dormitory that even featured a cafeteria.

Vanderbilt's finances were such that the charred ruins could not be removed for over a decade.  In 1940, bricks from the ruins were used to build the first non-nursing women's dorm on campus, McTyeire Hall.

properties.title: Vanderbilt Stadium
images: Vanderbilt Stadium was built in 1922 as the first purpose built college football stadium in the South.
It was also the largest in the South, with a seating capacity of over 20,000.
It was dedicated during the University of Michigan game that required a goal line stand to preserve a 0-0 tie.
The stadium has undergone numerous renovations and expansions and currently has a seating capacity of 40,550.

properties.title: Memorial Hall
images: Memorial Hall was built as a women's dormitory in 1933, in part with funds from the United Daughters of the Confederacy.
Originally named Confederate Memorial Hall, the University decided to rename the building Memorial Hall in 2002.
Memorial Hall is built in the Classical Revival style as evidenced by the pedimented portico, entablatures, and balustraded roof.
Memorial House was renovated in 1987 with additional modernization in the summers of 2006 and 2007.

properties.title: Old Central
images: Old Central is the oldest building on the Vanderbilt Campus. The building was home to Mr. and Mrs. Henry Foote.
Henry Foote had formerly been the Governor of Mississippi prior to relocating to Nashville.
The building was occupied by Union forces as the Union encampment and battle lines traversed the land that would eventually be part of campus.
Old Central currently houses the English Department and the Graduate Program in Economic Development.

properties.title: Sarratt Family Home Boxwoods
images: These boxwoods were transferred from C. Madison Sarratt's family home in 1974.
The transfer from the Gaffney, SC, estate was overseen by the Vanderbilt Garden Club.
C. Madison Sarratt, Mathmatics Professor and Dean of Students

properties.title: Bishop Johnson Center
images: Bishop Johnson Center was built as a faculty residence in 1900.
The building was formally the Student Christian Association House.
The building is named for Vanderbilt's first African American student, Joseph Johnson
The Bishop Johnson Black Cultural Center provides educational and cultural programing on the African American experience.

properties.title: Home Economics
images: Home Economics was built in 1914 and was the second structure erected on the Peabody campus.
The building serves as program offices and classroom space for graduate and undergraduate students.

properties.title: McGill Hall
images: Following World War II, returning soldiers were enrolling in college in very large numbers.
McGill Hall still serves as an upperclassmen dormitory.

properties.title: Commodore's Statue
images: The Commodore's Statue was created by the Italian-born sculptor Giuseppe Moretti in his New York studio.
The sculpture was commissioned by Nashville citizens and officers of the Tennessee Centennial Exposition.
The statue was originally placed at the western end of the Parthenon during the 1897 Tennessee Centennial Exposition.
Upon the closing of the exposition the statue was moved across the street to Vanderbilt's campus.
The statue was initially positioned in front of the Kirkland Hall Tower, but it was eventually moved to its current location in 1949.

properties.title: Peabody Library
images: Peabody Library was built in 1919 in the Classical Revival style as seen in the pedimented portico, entablatures, and balustraded roof.
The Peabody Library building was built with a gift from the Carnegie Corporation. The building was constructed from 1917-19 and opened its doors May 30, 1919.
The collection focuses on the areas of education, psychology, human development, and library and information science.
When Peabody College merged with Vanderbilt University in 1979, the Education Library became part of the University library system.

properties.title: Wyatt Center
images: The Faye and Joe Wyatt Center for Education, originally called the Social-Religious Building, was built in 1915 with funds donated by John D. Rockefeller.
The building has undergone extensive renovations with major additions of office and community space to the rear.
Wyatt Center presently serves as the Administrative and Technology Education Center.
The building boasts a large rotunda that is used for social events and lectures.

properties.title: Old Mechanical
images: The Mechanical Engineering Hall was the first facility built specifically for engineering education in the State of Tennessee.
It was funds donated by Cornelius II, the grandson of Commodore Vanderbilt, were used for the original construction.
The building was incorporated into the construction of the primary building for the Owen Graduate School of Management in 1982.

properties.title: Cohen Hall
images: Cohen Hall, originally called Cohen Art Building and Museum, was built in 1928.
Cohen Hall is built in the Classical Revival style as evidenced by the entablatures and balustraded roof.
Cohen Hall currently serves as the home of the Vanderbilt University Fine Arts Gallery. Admission to the gallery is free and open to the public.

properties.title: North Hall
images: North Hall was built in 1929 as a graduate dormitory.
North Hall was built in the Classical Revival style as evidenced by the entablatures and balustraded roof.
Now known as North House, it houses approximately 176 first-year students.
The building underwent an extensive renovation in 1989 and features an atrium on the sixth floor.

properties.title: Godchaux Hall
images: Godchaux Hall was built in the Collegiate Gothic style in 1925.
It was built to house the School of Nursing and now houses the school's faculty and administrative offices.
It was renamed in 1971 for Mary Ragland Godchaux in recognition of her family's contributions to the university.

properties.title: Furman Hall
images: Furman Hall was erected in 1907 in the style of a stone castle.
Furman Hall even features battlements which complement those that were added to Kirkland Hall after the 1905 fire.
The building was built with funds bequeathed to the University by Mrs. Francis Furman.
Mrs. Francis Furman dedicated the building to the memory of her beloved husband that had been a prominent Nashville merchant.
Furman currently houses the Humanities departments including Foreign Languages, Classical Studies, and Philosophy.

properties.title: Three Bishops and Garland
images: Bishop Holland McTyeire is buried here underneath the Magnolias while President of Vanderbilt.
In 1876 McTyeire oversaw the reburial of Bishops William McKendree and Joshua Soule reburied at this location.
McKendree was the first American-born Methodist bishop and had been a soldier with Washington at Yorktown when Cornwallis surrendered.
Soule was the descendant of Mayflower pilgrims and was influential in the formation of the Methodist Episcopal Church, South.
When Chancellor Garland died in 1895 his body was entombed here as well.
